  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="19" relname="span">
Intuitiveness is a concept, and if a design goal, needs to be tested in the early phases of 
design.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="1" relname="elaboration"> The UI part of development needs to be begin early in the lifecycle, not saved for 
later (or never).</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="16" relname="span"> Early testing is highly desirable over later testing.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="3" relname="volitional-cause"> Later testing in many 
cases, is just too late.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="3" relname="evidence"> What developers may think is intuitive, is not at all to common 
users.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="17" relname="span"> 

Most of the time, &quot;intuitiveness&quot; is used to market a product.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="14" relname="list"> We see things like &quot;This 
product is intuitive.&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="14" relname="list"> or &quot;On a scale of 1 -10, this product rates an 8 on intuitiveness.&quot; </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="13" relname="span">
These statements mean very little</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="9" relname="volitional-cause"> because intuitiveness is not tested well or often 
enough.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="18" relname="span"> The buzz word &quot;intuitiveness&quot; is most often used to sell, not to design.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="10" relname="evaluation"> Big 
difference.</segment>
